You need two things: a **navigation guard** in `AppShell` using `OnNavigating` + `GetDeferral()`, and **`BackButtonBehavior`** on the page.

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage.xaml`

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form here -->
</ContentPage>
```

### 2. ViewModel with dirty-tracking and back command

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    [RelayCommand]
    private async Task Back()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard) return;
        }

        HasUnsavedChanges = false; // so the guard doesn't double-prompt
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

### 3. Navigation guard in `AppShell.xaml.cs`

This catches the **hardware/gesture back** (Android back button, swipe) which bypasses `BackButtonBehavior.Command`:

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source != ShellNavigationSource.Pop)
        return;

    // Check if the current page's BindingContext has unsaved changes
    if (Shell.Current.CurrentPage?.BindingContext
            is EditProductViewModel vm && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();
        else
            vm.HasUnsavedChanges = false;

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- `GetDeferral()` is required because the confirmation is async — without it the navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- The guard checks `args.Source == Pop` so it only fires on back-navigation, not forward pushes.
- The `BackCommand` handles taps on the custom "Cancel" button; `OnNavigating` handles the system back gesture/button.
- Set `HasUnsavedChanges = false` before programmatic `GoToAsync("..")` to avoid the guard double-prompting.
